Introduction

In this project, we look at a data set with 79 variables on homes in Ames, Iowa. Then, we use Machine Learning to predict home prices.

Numeric Variables

There are a lot of variables in the data set. Lets use correlational analysis against the SalePrice to see if any variables have high correlation.

numericVars <- which(sapply(all, is.numeric)) #index vector numeric variables
numericVarNames <- names(numericVars) #saving names vector for use later on
cat('There are', length(numericVars), 'numeric variables')
There are 37 numeric variables
all_numVar <- all[, numericVars]
cor_numVar <- cor(all_numVar, use="pairwise.complete.obs") #correlations of all numeric variables

#sort on decreasing correlations with SalePrice
cor_sorted <- as.matrix(sort(cor_numVar[,'SalePrice'], decreasing = TRUE))

#select only high correlations
CorHigh <- names(which(apply(cor_sorted, 1, function(x) abs(x)>0.5)))
cor_numVar <- cor_numVar[CorHigh, CorHigh]

corrplot.mixed(cor_numVar, tl.col="black", tl.pos = "lt", number.cex=0.7)

We can see that OverallQual and GrLivArea(area of the home that is not the basement) is highly correlated with the SalePrice.

Some of the features are also correlated with one another - ie GarageCars and GarageArea (not surprising). We may consider excluding a few of these features with highly correlation to reduce dimensionality and potential overfitting in our model later.

Lets dive a bit further into some of these features that are highly correlated with SalePrice.

OverallQual

OverallQual is on a ten-point scale, with 10 being the highest rated (very excellent).

ggplot(data=all[!is.na(all$SalePrice),], aes(x=factor(OverallQual), y=SalePrice))+
        geom_boxplot(col='darkblue') + labs(x='Overall Quality') +
        scale_y_continuous(breaks= seq(0, 800000, by=100000), labels = comma)+
        coord_cartesian(ylim = c(0, 800000))

We see a positive correlation between SalePrice and OverallQual. There are outliers that exceed the 1.5*IQR in many of the OverallQual categories, but they appear to be reasonable outlier housing sale price rather than error, so we wont be removing them.

GrLivArea

ggplot(data=all[!is.na(all$SalePrice),], aes(x=GrLivArea, y=SalePrice))+
        geom_point(col='darkblue') + geom_smooth(method = "lm", se=FALSE, color="black", aes(group=1)) +
        scale_y_continuous(breaks= seq(0, 800000, by=100000), labels = comma) +
        geom_text_repel(aes(label = ifelse(GrLivArea[!is.na(SalePrice)]>4500, rownames(train), '')))

The SalePrice is positively correlated with GrLivArea which is not surprising as the greater the area of the home usually means higher housing prince. We see a few outliers with massive GrLivArea but low housing price (labelled 524 and 1299).

all[c(524, 1299), c(CorHigh)]

Looking at the two outliers more closely, we see that their OverallQual are both 10. Nothing in particular explains why the SalePrice could be low.

GarageCars

ggplot(data=all[!is.na(all$SalePrice),], aes(x=factor(GarageCars), y=SalePrice))+

There is a positive correlation between SalePrice and GarageCars until GarageCars exceeds 3.GarageCars may be just as highly correlated as OverallQual up to 3.

Lot

Three variables: LotFrontage, LotShape, LotConfig

colSums(is.na(all[c('LotFrontage','LotShape','LotConfig')]))
LotFrontage    LotShape   LotConfig 
        486           0           0
LotFrontage

Since we did not detect significant correlation between SalePrice and LotFrontage in our correlation analysis, we will assume the missing values are due to random events. LotFrontage may be related to the neighborhood in which the home is situated and we can assume the LotFrontage will be similar in homes in the same neighborhood. We can impute based on the median LotFrontage in each neighborhood. We will use missForest() to help us do that.

subset_data <- all[, c("LotFrontage", "Neighborhood")]

# Perform one-hot encoding on the 'Neighborhood' column
encoded_df <- model.matrix(~ Neighborhood - 1, data = subset_data)

# Convert the matrix to a dataframe
encoded_df <- as.data.frame(encoded_df)

# Combine the one-hot encoded neighborhood with the original 'LotFrontage' column
encoded_df <- cbind(subset_data$LotFrontage, encoded_df)

# Perform imputation using missForest
imputed_result <- missForest(encoded_df)

# Access the imputed values from the result object
imputed_values <- as.data.frame(imputed_result$ximp)

# Set imputed values
all$LotFrontage <- imputed_values[, c('subset_data$LotFrontage')]

Data Preparation for Model

Dropping features with high correlation

corrplot.mixed(cor_numVar, tl.col="black", tl.pos = "lt", number.cex=0.9)

We note that GarageArea + GarageCars have high correlation of 0.88; X1stFlrSF and TotalBsmtSF has correlation of 0.82; TotRmsAbvGrd and GrLivArea has correlation of 0.83. We will GarageArea in favor of GarageCars as GarageCars have higher correlation with SalePrice. We will drop variables that we have already created new features for (ie YearBuilt - Age and FullBath - TotalBath).

dropVars <- c('YearRemodAdd', 'YearBuilt','GarageArea', 'GarageType', 'GarageCars','FullBath','X1stFlrSF','TotalBsmtSF','GrLivArea','GarageYrBlt')
